    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1950-12-31T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1950-12-31T04:00:00-05:00" n="54"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d54">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">886A.2553/12–3150: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Saudi Arabia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hare</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Jidda</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1950-12-31T12:00:00+03:00"
                            >December 31, 1950—noon</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>417. From Brewer. <gloss target="#t_Aramco1">Aramco</gloss>–<gloss
                        target="#t_SAG1">SAG</gloss> negotiations concluded late last night December
                    30th, with agreement signed between Finance Minister and Davies in which profit
                    sharing principle put forward by company accepted by <gloss target="#t_SAG1"
                        >SAG</gloss> and outstanding <gloss target="#t_SAG1">SAG</gloss> demands
                    officially withdrawn. Company officials appear pleased with results, which they
                    terming “the December 1950 agreement”, stating that they gave in to <gloss
                        target="#t_SAG1">SAG</gloss> on a few minor points only to obtain agreement.
                    Entire <gloss target="#t_Aramco1">Aramco</gloss> party, including Owen, left by
                    plane for Luxor this morning, making it impossible obtain details agreement, but
                    George Hay and Bob Brougham proceeding directly Cairo and New York with signed
                    original. New York and Washington offices should have copies by January 3–4 and
                    have been asked communicate details Department soonest.<note n="1"
                        xml:id="d54fn1">Further documentation on the agreement is scheduled for
                        publication in a forthcoming volume of <hi rend="italic">Foreign
                            Relations</hi>.</note>
                </p>
                <p>For [Parker?]: Brougham hopes be in Cairo New Year’s Day and to see you.</p>
                <p>Sent Department 417; repeated information Dhahran 214, Cairo 91. [Brewer.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hare</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
